{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1779168770096,"sessionID":"ses_1c1475922ffeBFpIG9FNwSsGKw","part":{"id":"prt_e3eb8f82f001XyzC9kKe8q9kPr","messageID":"msg_e3eb8f212001hNn5U5YF16cY2I","sessionID":"ses_1c1475922ffeBFpIG9FNwSsGKw","snapshot":"c2f5fe58255fcbdc161e2a03bba8769810fc6b82","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1779168814087,"sessionID":"ses_1c1475922ffeBFpIG9FNwSsGKw","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_00_A3WJr8Jv77fDjpzhm8Gy4244","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/saifulpotential/Potential/nestfind-sample/.claude-project/nestfind/docs/PROJECT_KNOWLEDGE.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/saifulpotential/Potential/nestfind-sample/.claude-project/nestfind/docs/PROJECT_KNOWLEDGE.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # PROJECT_KNOWLEDGE\n2: \n3: ## Overview\n4: \n5: ### Application Purpose\n6: \n7: NestFind is a streamlined rental property listing platform that connects renters with available properties. The platform focuses exclusively on rentals, providing a clean and efficient browsing experience where renters can search, filter, view details, save favorites, and submit inquiries to property managers. An accompanying admin dashboard enables administrators to manage property listings, respond to inquiries, and oversee user accounts.\n8: \n9: The platform targets two primary user groups: Renters who browse and discover rental properties, and Administrators who manage the listings and respond to renter inquiries. NestFind integrates with Google Maps for property location display.\n10: \n11: ### Technology Stack\n12: \n13: | Layer | Technology |\n14: |-------|------------|\n15: | Backend | NestJS 11, TypeScript 5.7+ |\n16: | Frontend | React 19 with React Router 7 (framework mode) |\n17: | Database | PostgreSQL 16 |\n18: | ORM | TypeORM 0.3.x |\n19: | Authentication | JWT via httpOnly cookies (Access: 1h, Refresh: 7d) |\n20: | API Documentation | Swagger/OpenAPI |\n21: | Validation | class-validator (backend), Zod (frontend) |\n22: | Frontend State | Redux Toolkit with createAsyncThunk |\n23: | Styling | Tailwind CSS 4, Shadcn/UI |\n24: | Maps | Google Maps API |\n25: | Deployment | Docker |\n26: \n27: ### Domain\n28: \n29: `nestfind.com` — web application\n30: \n31: ---\n32: \n33: ## User Roles\n34: \n35: | Role | Description | Permissions |\n36: |------|-------------|-------------|\n37: | **Renter** | Browses rental property listings, views detailed property information, saves properties to favorites, and submits inquiries to property managers. | `browse_properties`, `view_property_details`, `save_favorites`, `submit_inquiries` |\n38: | **Admin** | Has full system access to manage property listings (CRUD), manage user accounts, view and respond to inquiries from renters. | `manage_properties`, `manage_users`, `view_inquiries`, `respond_to_inquiries` |\n39: | **Guest** | Unauthenticated visitor who can browse public property listings and view property details. Must register/login to save favorites or submit inquiries. | `browse_properties`, `view_property_details` |\n40: \n41: ### Authentication & Authorization\n42: \n43: - **JWT via httpOnly cookies**: Access token (1 hour) + Refresh token (7 days). Cookies configured with `httpOnly: true, secure: true, sameSite: 'strict'`. Tokens are never stored in localStorage.\n44: - **Role-based access control (RBAC)**: Guards at the route/endpoint level enforce role-specific permissions via `JwtAuthGuard` + `RolesGuard`.\n45: - **Guest access**: Public endpoints for browsing and viewing properties are marked with `@Public()` decorator; all other endpoints require authentication.\n46: - **Admin assignment**: Admin accounts are created by existing admins or via database seeding. Self-registration defaults to Renter role.\n47: \n48: ---\n49: \n50: ## Core Features\n51: \n52: ### Common (All Users)\n53: \n54: - **Authentication**\n55:   - User login with email + password\n56:   - JWT access token (1h) and refresh token (7d) via httpOnly cookies\n57:   - Token refresh mechanism with rotation\n58:   - Logout clears cookies\n59: \n60: - **Registration**\n61:   - Self-service sign-up with name, email, password, phone (optional)\n62:   - Default role assignment: Renter\n63:   - Email verification (optional, configurable)\n64: \n65: - **Password Reset**\n66:   - Forgot password flow via email\n67:   - Secure reset token with expiration\n68: \n69: ### Renter Features\n70: \n71: 1. **Property Search**\n72:    - Search by location (text input or current geolocation)\n73:    - Real-time filtering by price range, number of bedrooms, property type\n74:    - Results displayed as property cards with thumbnail, price, and key details\n75:    - Pagination or infinite scroll for large result sets\n76: \n77: 2. **Property Detail View**\n78:    - Full property page with photo gallery, amenities list, description, and floor plan\n79:    - Embedded Google Map showing property location\n80:    - Save to favorites (toggle)\n81:    - Contact / Submit Inquiry button\n82: \n83: 3. **Favorites Management**\n84:    - View all saved/favorited properties\n85:    - Remove properties from favorites\n86:    - Quick access from navigation\n87: \n88: 4. **Submit Inquiry**\n89:    - Contact form on property detail page (name, email, phone, message)\n90:    - Form validation before submission\n91:    - Confirmation message shown to renter\n92:    - Admin notified of new inquiry\n93: \n94: ### Admin Features\n95: \n96: 1. **Admin Dashboard**\n97:    - Overview statistics: total properties, total inquiries, recent activity\n98:    - Quick links to property management and inquiry management\n99: \n100: 2. **Property Management (CRUD)**\n101:    - List all properties with search, filter, and pagination\n102:    - Add new property with details: title, description, price, bedrooms, bathrooms, property type, address, amenities, photos (multi-upload)\n103:    - Edit existing property information\n104:    - Delete or archive property listings (soft delete)\n105: \n106: 3. **Inquiry Management**\n107:    - View all inquiries with status (new, read, responded)\n108:    - Mark inquiries as read\n109:    - Respond to inquiries directly from the dashboard\n110:    - Filter by property or renter\n111: \n112: 4. **User Management**\n113:    - View list of registered renters\n114:    - View renter details and activity history\n115:    - Suspend or reactivate user accounts\n116: \n117: ---\n118: \n119: ## Functional Requirements\n120: \n121: ### Authentication\n122: \n123: - **FR-AUTH-001**: Users must authenticate with email and password to access protected features.\n124: - **FR-AUTH-002**: JWT access tokens expire after 1 hour; refresh tokens expire after 7 days.\n125: - **FR-AUTH-003**: Refresh tokens are rotated on each use (old token invalidated).\n126: - **FR-AUTH-004**: All authentication tokens are stored in httpOnly, secure, sameSite-strict cookies.\n127: - **FR-AUTH-005**: Guest users can browse properties without authentication.\n128: \n129: ### Property Search\n130: \n131: - **FR-SEARCH-001**: Renters can search properties by location text (city, neighborhood, zip code).\n132: - **FR-SEARCH-002**: Renters can use browser geolocation to find properties near their current location.\n133: - **FR-SEARCH-003**: Results support filtering by price range (min/max), number of bedrooms, and property type.\n134: - **FR-SEARCH-004**: Filters update results in real-time without full page reload.\n135: - **FR-SEARCH-005**: Each result card displays thumbnail image, price, address, bedrooms, and bathrooms.\n136: \n137: ### Property Details\n138: \n139: - **FR-DETAIL-001**: Property detail page displays full photo gallery with navigation.\n140: - **FR-DETAIL-002**: Property page includes description, amenities list, pricing, and property specifications.\n141: - **FR-DETAIL-003**: An embedded Google Map shows the property location with a pin marker.\n142: - **FR-DETAIL-004**: Authenticated renters can toggle the property as a favorite.\n143: - **FR-DETAIL-005**: A Contact/Inquiry button is prominently displayed.\n144: \n145: ### Inquiries\n146: \n147: - **FR-INQ-001**: Inquiry form collects name, email, phone (optional), and message.\n148: - **FR-INQ-002**: Form fields are validated client-side (Zod) and server-side (class-validator).\n149: - **FR-INQ-003**: On successful submission, renter sees a confirmation message.\n150: - **FR-INQ-004**: System notifies admin of new inquiries (in-dashboard notification).\n151: \n152: ### Admin: Property Management\n153: \n154: - **FR-ADM-PROP-001**: Admin can create new property listings with all required fields.\n155: - **FR-ADM-PROP-002**: Admin can upload multiple photos per property.\n156: - **FR-ADM-PROP-003**: Admin can edit all fields of an existing property.\n157: - **FR-ADM-PROP-004**: Admin can soft-delete (archive) a property listing.\n158: - **FR-ADM-PROP-005**: Property list supports search, sort, and pagination.\n159: \n160: ### Admin: Inquiry Management\n161: \n162: - **FR-ADM-INQ-001**: Admin can view all inquiries with status indicators.\n163: - **FR-ADM-INQ-002**: Admin can filter inquiries by property or renter.\n164: - **FR-ADM-INQ-003**: Admin can mark inquiries as read and respond to them.\n165: \n166: ### Admin: User Management\n167: \n168: - **FR-ADM-USER-001**: Admin can view a list of all registered renters.\n169: - **FR-ADM-USER-002**: Admin can view individual renter details and activity.\n170: - **FR-ADM-USER-003**: Admin can suspend or reactivate user accounts.\n171: \n172: ---\n173: \n174: ## Non-Functional Requirements\n175: \n176: ### Performance\n177: \n178: - **NFR-PERF-001**: Property search results must return within 500ms for typical query loads.\n179: - **NFR-PERF-002**: Image assets should be served with lazy loading and optimized formats (WebP).\n180: - **NFR-PERF-003**: API responses must use pagination for list endpoints (default: 20 items/page).\n181: \n182: ### Security\n183: \n184: - **NFR-SEC-001**: All authenticated endpoints enforce JWT validation via guards.\n185: - **NFR-SEC-002**: Passwords are hashed using bcrypt with appropriate salt rounds.\n186: - **NFR-SEC-003**: Input validation is enforced at the API boundary using class-validator/Zod.\n187: - **NFR-SEC-004**: CORS is configured to allow only the frontend origin.\n188: - **NFR-SEC-005**: Rate limiting is applied to authentication endpoints (login, register, password reset).\n189: \n190: ### Reliability\n191: \n192: - **NFR-REL-001**: Database operations use transactions for multi-step mutations.\n193: - **NFR-REL-002**: Soft delete (`deleted_at`) is used for properties and user accounts (no destructive deletes).\n194: - **NFR-REL-003**: API errors return consistent response format with appropriate HTTP status codes.\n195: \n196: ### Maintainability\n197: \n198: - **NFR-MAIN-001**: Backend follows the 4-layer architecture pattern: Controller → Service → Repository → Entity.\n199: - **NFR-MAIN-002**: All backend layers extend base classes (`BaseController`, `BaseService`, `BaseRepository`, `BaseEntity`).\n200: - **NFR-MAIN-003**: Frontend follows file organization patterns defined in `.claude/react/docs/file-organization.md`.\n201: - **NFR-MAIN-004**: All API endpoints are documented with Swagger/OpenAPI annotations.\n202: \n203: ### Compatibility\n204: \n205: - **NFR-COMP-001**: Frontend supports latest 2 versions of Chrome, Firefox, Safari, and Edge.\n206: - **NFR-COMP-002**: Application is responsive and functional on mobile, tablet, and desktop viewports.\n207: \n208: ---\n209: \n210: ## Ontology / Glossary\n211: \n212: | Term | Definition |\n213: |------|------------|\n214: | **Property** | A rental property listing with details such as title, description, price, address, bedrooms, bathrooms, property type, amenities, and photos. |\n215: | **Property Type** | The category of rental property (e.g., apartment, house, condo, townhouse, studio). |\n216: | **Listing** | A published property that is visible to renters in search results. |\n217: | **Renter** | A registered user who browses, searches, and saves properties, and submits inquiries. |\n218: | **Admin** | A system administrator with full access to manage properties, users, and inquiries. |\n219: | **Guest** | An unauthenticated visitor who can browse and view property details. |\n220: | **Inquiry** | A contact form submission from a renter about a specific property, containing name, email, phone (optional), and message. |\n221: | **Favorites** | A saved collection of properties that a renter has bookmarked for later reference. |\n222: | **Amenity** | A feature or facility available at a property (e.g., parking, laundry, gym, pool, air conditioning). |\n223: | **Soft Delete** | A record is marked as deleted (`deleted_at` timestamp) but remains in the database, allowing recovery and audit trails. |\n224: | **Archive** | A property listing that has been soft-deleted by an admin, removing it from public search results. |\n225: | **httpOnly Cookie** | A cookie that is inaccessible to client-side JavaScript, used to store JWT tokens securely. |\n226: | **Access Token** | A short-lived JWT (1 hour) that authorizes API requests. |\n227: | **Refresh Token** | A longer-lived JWT (7 days) used to obtain new access tokens without re-authentication. |\n228: | **RBAC** | Role-Based Access Control — restricts system access based on user roles (Renter, Admin). |\n229: | **JwtAuthGuard** | A NestJS guard that validates JWT from httpOnly cookies on protected routes. |\n230: | **RolesGuard** | A NestJS guard that checks user role permissions for accessing specific endpoints. |\n231: | **BaseController** | A base class providing automatic CRUD endpoints for controllers that extend it. |\n232: | **BaseService** | A base class providing automatic CRUD business logic for services that extend it. |\n233: | **BaseRepository** | A base class providing automatic TypeORM CRUD operations for repositories that extend it. |\n234: | **BaseEntity** | A base class providing UUID primary key, timestamps (`createdAt`, `updatedAt`), and soft delete (`deletedAt`) for all entities. |\n235: | **createAsyncThunk** | Redux Toolkit utility for creating async thunk actions for API calls in the frontend. |\n236: | **React Router 7 (Framework Mode)** | The routing system used by the frontend, where routes are defined declaratively using `route()`, `layout()`, and `index()` from `@react-router/dev/routes`. |\n237: \n238: ---\n239: \n240: ## Architecture Overview\n241: \n242: ### Backend: Four-Layer Architecture\n243: \n244: ```\n245: HTTP Request\n246:     ↓\n247: Controller  (extends BaseController)  — HTTP handling, validation, Swagger docs\n248:     ↓\n249: Service     (extends BaseService)     — Business logic, rules enforcement\n250:     ↓\n251: Repository  (extends BaseRepository)  — Data access, TypeORM queries\n252:     ↓\n253: Entity      (extends BaseEntity)      — Database schema (UUID PK, timestamps, soft delete)\n254:     ↓\n255: PostgreSQL + TypeORM\n256: ```\n257: \n258: ### Frontend Architecture\n259: \n260: - **Routing**: React Router 7 framework mode with `routes.ts` defining `route()`, `layout()`, `index()` patterns\n261: - **State Management**: Redux Toolkit with `createAsyncThunk` for API data fetching; Redux slices per domain feature\n262: - **Forms**: React Hook Form + Zod validation following shadcn/ui patterns\n263: - **Auth**: JWT httpOnly cookies with AuthContext, GuestGuard, and AuthGuard components\n264: - **Source Directory**: `app/` (not `src/`), imports use `~/` alias\n265: - **Styling**: Tailwind CSS 4 + Shadcn/UI component library\n266: \n267: ### Directory Structure\n268: \n269: ```\n270: nestfind/\n271: ├── backend/\n272: │   ├── src/\n273: │   │   ├── core/              # Base classes, guards, decorators, filters\n274: │   │   │   ├── base/          # BaseEntity, BaseRepository, BaseService, BaseController\n275: │   │   │   ├── decorators/    # @Public(), @Roles(), @CurrentUser()\n276: │   │   │   ├── guards/        # JwtAuthGuard, RolesGuard\n277: │   │   │   ├── filters/       # HttpExceptionFilter\n278: │   │   │   ├── interceptors/  # TransformInterceptor, LoggingInterceptor\n279: │   │   │   └── pipes/         # ValidationPipe\n280: │   │   ├── modules/           # Feature modules (entity, repo, service, controller, module)\n281: │   │   ├── infrastructure/    # External services (mail, s3, token)\n282: │   │   └── database/          # Migrations, seeds\n283: │   └── test/                  # E2E tests\n284: ├── frontend/\n285: │   └── app/                   # Source directory\n286: │       ├── components/        # ui/, atoms/, modals/, shared/, layouts/, guards/\n287: │       ├── pages/             # Route pages\n288: │       ├── services/          # httpService.ts, httpMethods/, httpServices/\n289: │       ├── redux/             # features/, store/\n290: │       ├── types/             # .d.ts per domain\n291: │       ├── enums/             # Synced from backend\n292: │       ├── contexts/          # AuthContext\n293: │       ├── hooks/             # Custom hooks\n294: │       ├── lib/               # cn() utility\n295: │       ├── utils/             # errorHandler, validations/\n296: │       └── styles/            # Tailwind + theme variables\n297: └── docker-compose.yml\n298: ```\n299: \n300: ### API Base URLs\n301: \n302: | Environment | URL |\n303: |-------------|-----|\n304: | Development | `http://localhost:3000/api` |\n305: | Staging | `https://staging.nestfind.com/api` |\n306: | Production | `https://api.nestfind.com/api` |\n307: \n308: ---\n309: \n310: ## Related Documentation\n311: \n312: - [API Documentation](PROJECT_API.md) — Complete API endpoint specifications\n313: - [Database Schema](PROJECT_DATABASE.md) — Entity definitions and relationships\n314: - [API Integration](PROJECT_API_INTEGRATION.md) — Frontend-backend integration mapping\n315: - [Backend API Status](../status/backend/API_IMPLEMENTATION_STATUS.md) — Backend implementation tracking\n316: - [Frontend Screen Status](../status/frontend/SCREEN_IMPLEMENTATION_STATUS.md) — Frontend implementation tracking\n317: - [Architecture Decisions](../memory/DECISIONS.md) — Key technical decisions log\n318: - [Coding Patterns](../memory/LEARNINGS.md) — Patterns and insights\n319: \n320: ---\n321: \n322: *Generated: 2026-05-19 | Source: seed.yaml + architecture guides*\n\n(End of file - total 322 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# PROJECT_KNOWLEDGE\n\n## Overview\n\n### Application Purpose\n\nNestFind is a streamlined rental property listing platform that connects renters with available properties. The platform focuses exclusively on rentals, providing a clean and efficient browsing experience where renters can search, filter, view details, save favorites, and submit inquiries to property managers. An accompanying admin dashboard enables administrators to manage property listings, respond to inquiries, and oversee user accounts.\n\nThe platform targets two primary user groups: Renters who browse and discover rental properties, and Administrators who manage the listings and respond to renter inquiries. NestFind integrates with Google Maps for property location display.\n\n### Technology Stack\n\n| Layer | Technology |\n|-------|------------|\n| Backend | NestJS 11, TypeScript 5.7+ |\n| Frontend | React 19 with React Router 7 (framework mode) |\n| Database | PostgreSQL 16 |\n| ORM | TypeORM 0.3.x |\n| Authentication | JWT via httpOnly cookies (Access: 1h, Refresh: 7d) |\n| API Documentation | Swagger/OpenAPI |","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".claude-project/nestfind/docs/PROJECT_KNOWLEDGE.md","time":{"start":1779168813792,"end":1779168814084}},"id":"prt_e3eb99d3c001ER8ULd4cL3fpl4","sessionID":"ses_1c1475922ffeBFpIG9FNwSsGKw","messageID":"msg_e3eb8f212001hNn5U5YF16cY2I"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1779168815920,"sessionID":"ses_1c1475922ffeBFpIG9FNwSsGKw","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_01_Vwucowbw3NXNu8Z3sXBx4879","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/saifulpotential/Potential/nestfind-sample/.claude-project/nestfind/docs/PROJECT_DATABASE.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/saifulpotential/Potential/nestfind-sample/.claude-project/nestfind/docs/PROJECT_DATABASE.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # PROJECT_DATABASE\n2: \n3: ## Schema Overview\n4: \n5: All entities extend `BaseEntity` which provides:\n6: - `id` — UUID primary key\n7: - `createdAt` — `timestamp` (auto-managed)\n8: - `updatedAt` — `timestamp` (auto-managed)\n9: - `deletedAt` — `timestamp | null` (soft delete support)\n10: \n11: Column naming convention: `snake_case` in the database (`@CreateDateColumn({ name: 'created_at' })`).\n12: \n13: ---\n14: \n15: ## Entities\n16: \n17: ### User\n18: \n19: Represents all registered users (Renters and Admins). Extends `BaseEntity` with soft delete.\n20: \n21: **Table:** `users`\n22: \n23: | Field | Type | Constraints | Description |\n24: |-------|------|-------------|-------------|\n25: | `id` | `uuid` | PK, default: `uuid_generate_v4()` | Inherited from BaseEntity |\n26: | `name` | `varchar(100)` | NOT NULL | User's full name |\n27: | `email` | `varchar(255)` | UNIQUE, NOT NULL | Login email address |\n28: | `password` | `varchar(255)` | NOT NULL | bcrypt-hashed password |\n29: | `phone` | `varchar(20)` | NULLABLE | Optional phone number |\n30: | `role` | `enum` (`RoleEnum`) | NOT NULL, default: `'renter'` | `renter` \\| `admin` |\n31: | `status` | `enum` (`UserStatusEnum`) | NOT NULL, default: `'active'` | `active` \\| `suspended` |\n32: | `email_verified_at` | `timestamp` | NULLABLE | Null until email verification completes |\n33: | `created_at` | `timestamp` | NOT NULL, default: `now()` | Inherited from BaseEntity |\n34: | `updated_at` | `timestamp` | NOT NULL, default: `now()` | Inherited from BaseEntity |\n35: | `deleted_at` | `timestamp` | NULLABLE | Soft delete timestamp |\n36: \n37: **Indexes:**\n38: - `UNIQUE` on `email`\n39: - `INDEX` on `role`\n40: - `INDEX` on `status`\n41: - `INDEX` on `(role, status)` composite\n42: \n43: **Relationships:**\n44: - `hasMany` → `RefreshToken` (one user has many refresh tokens)\n45: - `hasMany` → `PasswordResetToken` (one user has many reset tokens)\n46: - `hasMany` → `Favorite` (one user has many favorites)\n47: - `hasMany` → `Inquiry` (one user submits many inquiries)\n48: \n49: ---\n50: \n51: ### RefreshToken\n52: \n53: Stores JWT refresh tokens for rotation and invalidation. Each refresh creates a new row; the old row is marked deleted when rotated. Not extending `BaseEntity` (no need for update timestamps or soft delete — expiries handle lifecycle).\n54: \n55: **Table:** `refresh_tokens`\n56: \n57: | Field | Type | Constraints | Description |\n58: |-------|------|-------------|-------------|\n59: | `id` | `uuid` | PK, default: `uuid_generate_v4()` | Primary key |\n60: | `user_id` | `uuid` | FK → `users.id`, NOT NULL, ON DELETE CASCADE | Owning user |\n61: | `token` | `varchar(500)` | NOT NULL, UNIQUE | Encoded JWT refresh token string |\n62: | `expires_at` | `timestamp` | NOT NULL | Token expiration time (7 days from issue) |\n63: | `revoked_at` | `timestamp` | NULLABLE | Set when token is rotated or user logs out |\n64: | `created_at` | `timestamp` | NOT NULL, default: `now()` | Token creation time |\n65: \n66: **Indexes:**\n67: - `UNIQUE` on `token`\n68: - `INDEX` on `user_id`\n69: - `INDEX` on `expires_at`\n70: \n71: **Relationships:**\n72: - `belongsTo` → `User` via `user_id`\n73: \n74: ---\n75: \n76: ### PasswordResetToken\n77: \n78: Stores tokens for the forgot-password / reset-password flow. Tokens expire after a configurable window (e.g., 1 hour).\n79: \n80: **Table:** `password_reset_tokens`\n81: \n82: | Field | Type | Constraints | Description |\n83: |-------|------|-------------|-------------|\n84: | `id` | `uuid` | PK, default: `uuid_generate_v4()` | Primary key |\n85: | `user_id` | `uuid` | FK → `users.id`, NOT NULL, ON DELETE CASCADE | Owning user |\n86: | `token` | `varchar(500)` | NOT NULL, UNIQUE | Secure random reset token |\n87: | `expires_at` | `timestamp` | NOT NULL | Token expiry (e.g., 1 hour from creation) |\n88: | `used_at` | `timestamp` | NULLABLE | Set when password is successfully reset |\n89: | `created_at` | `timestamp` | NOT NULL, default: `now()` | Token creation time |\n90: \n91: **Indexes:**\n92: - `UNIQUE` on `token`\n93: - `INDEX` on `user_id`\n94: \n95: **Relationships:**\n96: - `belongsTo` → `User` via `user_id`\n97: \n98: ---\n99: \n100: ### Property\n101: \n102: Represents a rental property listing. Supports soft delete (archiving). Address fields are stored as individual columns for search/indexing; API layer nests them into an `address` object.\n103: \n104: **Table:** `properties`\n105: \n106: | Field | Type | Constraints | Description |\n107: |-------|------|-------------|-------------|\n108: | `id` | `uuid` | PK, default: `uuid_generate_v4()` | Inherited from BaseEntity |\n109: | `title` | `varchar(200)` | NOT NULL | Listing title (5–200 chars) |\n110: | `description` | `text` | NOT NULL | Full description (20–5000 chars) |\n111: | `price` | `decimal(10,2)` | NOT NULL | Monthly rent (> 0) |\n112: | `bedrooms` | `integer` | NOT NULL, CHECK (≥ 0) | Number of bedrooms |\n113: | `bathrooms` | `integer` | NOT NULL, CHECK (≥ 0) | Number of bathrooms |\n114: | `square_feet` | `integer` | NULLABLE, CHECK (> 0) | Living area in square feet |\n115: | `property_type` | `enum` (`PropertyTypeEnum`) | NOT NULL | `apartment` \\| `house` \\| `condo` \\| `townhouse` \\| `studio` |\n116: | `address_street` | `varchar(200)` | NOT NULL | Street address |\n117: | `address_city` | `varchar(100)` | NOT NULL | City |\n118: | `address_state` | `varchar(100)` | NOT NULL | State / province |\n119: | `address_zip_code` | `varchar(10)` | NOT NULL | ZIP / postal code |\n120: | `address_latitude` | `decimal(10,7)` | NULLABLE | Geocoordinate latitude (-90 to 90) |\n121: | `address_longitude` | `decimal(10,7)` | NULLABLE | Geocoordinate longitude (-180 to 180) |\n122: | `available_from` | `date` | NULLABLE | Date property becomes available |\n123: | `created_at` | `timestamp` | NOT NULL, default: `now()` | Inherited from BaseEntity |\n124: | `updated_at` | `timestamp` | NOT NULL, default: `now()` | Inherited from BaseEntity |\n125: | `deleted_at` | `timestamp` | NULLABLE | Soft delete / archive timestamp |\n126: \n127: **Indexes:**\n128: - `INDEX` on `property_type`\n129: - `INDEX` on `price`\n130: - `INDEX` on `bedrooms`\n131: - `INDEX` on `bathrooms`\n132: - `INDEX` on `address_city`\n133: - `INDEX` on `address_state`\n134: - `INDEX` on `(address_latitude, address_longitude)` — geospatial queries\n135: - `GIN INDEX` or `tsvector` on `title || ' ' || description || ' ' || address_city || ' ' || address_state` for full-text search (optional, for performance at scale)\n136: \n137: **Relationships:**\n138: - `hasMany` → `PropertyPhoto` (one property has many photos)\n139: - `belongsToMany` → `Amenity` via `property_amenities` junction\n140: - `hasMany` → `Favorite` (one property is favorited by many users)\n141: - `hasMany` → `Inquiry` (one property receives many inquiries)\n142: \n143: ---\n144: \n145: ### PropertyPhoto\n146: \n147: Stores uploaded photos for a property. Multiple photos per property with ordering and a primary photo designation.\n148: \n149: **Table:** `property_photos`\n150: \n151: | Field | Type | Constraints | Description |\n152: |-------|------|-------------|-------------|\n153: | `id` | `uuid` | PK, default: `uuid_generate_v4()` | Inherited from BaseEntity |\n154: | `property_id` | `uuid` | FK → `properties.id`, NOT NULL, ON DELETE CASCADE | Owning property |\n155: | `url` | `varchar(500)` | NOT NULL | Photo URL (S3 / CDN path) |\n156: | `is_primary` | `boolean` | NOT NULL, default: `false` | Whether this is the main/thumbnail photo |\n157: | `sort_order` | `integer` | NOT NULL, default: `0` | Display order in gallery |\n158: | `created_at` | `timestamp` | NOT NULL, default: `now()` | Inherited from BaseEntity |\n159: | `updated_at` | `timestamp` | NOT NULL, default: `now()` | Inherited from BaseEntity |\n160: \n161: **Indexes:**\n162: - `INDEX` on `property_id`\n163: - `INDEX` on `(property_id, sort_order)`\n164: \n165: **Business Rule:** Only one photo per property may have `is_primary = true`. Enforced at the application layer.\n166: \n167: **Relationships:**\n168: - `belongsTo` → `Property` via `property_id`\n169: \n170: ---\n171: \n172: ### Amenity\n173: \n174: Predefined list of amenities that can be associated with properties. Managed by admins.\n175: \n176: **Table:** `amenities`\n177: \n178: | Field | Type | Constraints | Description |\n179: |-------|------|-------------|-------------|\n180: | `id` | `uuid` | PK, default: `uuid_generate_v4()` | Inherited from BaseEntity |\n181: | `name` | `varchar(50)` | UNIQUE, NOT NULL | Amenity name (e.g., \"parking\", \"gym\") |\n182: | `icon` | `varchar(50)` | NOT NULL | Icon identifier for frontend rendering |\n183: | `created_at` | `timestamp` | NOT NULL, default: `now()` | Inherited from BaseEntity |\n184: | `updated_at` | `timestamp` | NOT NULL, default: `now()` | Inherited from BaseEntity |\n185: | `deleted_at` | `timestamp` | NULLABLE | Soft delete |\n186: \n187: **Indexes:**\n188: - `UNIQUE` on `name`\n189: \n190: **Relationships:**\n191: - `belongsToMany` → `Property` via `property_amenities` junction\n192: \n193: ---\n194: \n195: ### PropertyAmenity\n196: \n197: Junction table for the many-to-many relationship between `Property` and `Amenity`. Each row links one property to one amenity.\n198: \n199: **Table:** `property_amenities`\n200: \n201: | Field | Type | Constraints | Description |\n202: |-------|------|-------------|-------------|\n203: | `property_id` | `uuid` | PK (composite), FK → `properties.id`, NOT NULL, ON DELETE CASCADE | Property reference |\n204: | `amenity_id` | `uuid` | PK (composite), FK → `amenities.id`, NOT NULL, ON DELETE CASCADE | Amenity reference |\n205: \n206: **Primary Key:** Composite `(property_id, amenity_id)`\n207: \n208: **Indexes:**\n209: - `INDEX` on `amenity_id`\n210: \n211: **Relationships:**\n212: - `belongsTo` → `Property` via `property_id`\n213: - `belongsTo` → `Amenity` via `amenity_id`\n214: \n215: ---\n216: \n217: ### Favorite\n218: \n219: Represents a renter saving a property to their favorites. Idempotent — adding a duplicate returns the existing record (API handles this). Composite unique constraint prevents duplicates.\n220: \n221: **Table:** `favorites`\n222: \n223: | Field | Type | Constraints | Description |\n224: |-------|------|-------------|-------------|\n225: | `id` | `uuid` | PK, default: `uuid_generate_v4()` | Inherited from BaseEntity |\n226: | `user_id` | `uuid` | FK → `users.id`, NOT NULL, ON DELETE CASCADE | The renter who favorited |\n227: | `property_id` | `uuid` | FK → `properties.id`, NOT NULL, ON DELETE CASCADE | The favorited property |\n228: | `created_at` | `timestamp` | NOT NULL, default: `now()` | Inherited from BaseEntity |\n229: \n230: **Indexes:**\n231: - `UNIQUE` on `(user_id, property_id)` — prevents duplicate favorites\n232: - `INDEX` on `user_id`\n233: - `INDEX` on `property_id`\n234: \n235: **Relationships:**\n236: - `belongsTo` → `User` via `user_id`\n237: - `belongsTo` → `Property` via `property_id`\n238: \n239: ---\n240: \n241: ### Inquiry\n242: \n243: Represents a contact/inquiry submission from a renter about a specific property. Admins manage inquiry status and responses.\n244: \n245: **Table:** `inquiries`\n246: \n247: | Field | Type | Constraints | Description |\n248: |-------|------|-------------|-------------|\n249: | `id` | `uuid` | PK, default: `uuid_generate_v4()` | Inherited from BaseEntity |\n250: | `property_id` | `uuid` | FK → `properties.id`, NOT NULL, ON DELETE SET NULL | Subject property |\n251: | `user_id` | `uuid` | FK → `users.id`, NOT NULL, ON DELETE SET NULL | Submitting renter |\n252: | `name` | `varchar(100)` | NOT NULL | Submitter's name (denormalized for display) |\n253: | `email` | `varchar(255)` | NOT NULL | Submitter's email (denormalized) |\n254: | `phone` | `varchar(20)` | NULLABLE | Submitter's phone (denormalized) |\n255: | `message` | `text` | NOT NULL | Inquiry message body (10–2000 chars) |\n256: | `status` | `enum` (`InquiryStatusEnum`) | NOT NULL, default: `'new'` | `new` \\| `read` \\| `responded` |\n257: | `response` | `text` | NULLABLE | Admin's response text |\n258: | `responded_at` | `timestamp` | NULLABLE | Set when admin responds |\n259: | `created_at` | `timestamp` | NOT NULL, default: `now()` | Inherited from BaseEntity |\n260: | `updated_at` | `timestamp` | NOT NULL, default: `now()` | Inherited from BaseEntity |\n261: \n262: **Note:** `name`, `email`, `phone` are denormalized from the `User` record at submission time. This preserves the inquiry even if the user account is later deleted (hence `ON DELETE SET NULL` on `user_id`).\n263: \n264: **Indexes:**\n265: - `INDEX` on `property_id`\n266: - `INDEX` on `user_id`\n267: - `INDEX` on `status`\n268: - `INDEX` on `(status, created_at)` — for admin dashboard filtering\n269: \n270: **Relationships:**\n271: - `belongsTo` → `Property` via `property_id`\n272: - `belongsTo` → `User` via `user_id`\n273: \n274: ---\n275: \n276: ## Enums\n277: \n278: ### RoleEnum\n279: \n280: Used in `users.role`.\n281: \n282: | Value | Description |\n283: |-------|-------------|\n284: | `renter` | Standard user who browses and saves properties, submits inquiries |\n285: | `admin` | Administrator with full system access |\n286: \n287: ---\n288: \n289: ### UserStatusEnum\n290: \n291: Used in `users.status`.\n292: \n293: | Value | Description |\n294: |-------|-------------|\n295: | `active` | Account in good standing |\n296: | `suspended` | Account suspended by admin; cannot log in |\n297: \n298: ---\n299: \n300: ### PropertyTypeEnum\n301: \n302: Used in `properties.property_type`.\n303: \n304: | Value | Description |\n305: |-------|-------------|\n306: | `apartment` | Apartment unit |\n307: | `house` | Single-family house |\n308: | `condo` | Condominium |\n309: | `townhouse` | Townhouse |\n310: | `studio` | Studio apartment |\n311: \n312: ---\n313: \n314: ### InquiryStatusEnum\n315: \n316: Used in `inquiries.status`.\n317: \n318: | Value | Description |\n319: |-------|-------------|\n320: | `new` | Unread inquiry (default on submission) |\n321: | `read` | Viewed by admin |\n322: | `responded` | Admin has sent a response |\n323: \n324: ---\n325: \n326: ## Relationships\n327: \n328: ### Entity Relationship Diagram\n329: \n330: ```\n331: users (1) ────────< (many) refresh_tokens\n332: users (1) ────────< (many) password_reset_tokens\n333: users (1) ────────< (many) favorites\n334: users (1) ────────< (many) inquiries\n335: \n336: properties (1) ───< (many) property_photos\n337: properties (1) ───< (many) favorites\n338: properties (1) ───< (many) inquiries\n339: properties (many) >────< (many) amenities  [via property_amenities]\n340: ```\n341: \n342: ### Foreign Key Summary\n343: \n344: | Child Table | FK Column | Parent Table | On Delete |\n345: |-------------|----------|--------------|-----------|\n346: | `refresh_tokens` | `user_id` | `users.id` | CASCADE |\n347: | `password_reset_tokens` | `user_id` | `users.id` | CASCADE |\n348: | `property_photos` | `property_id` | `properties.id` | CASCADE |\n349: | `property_amenities` | `property_id` | `properties.id` | CASCADE |\n350: | `property_amenities` | `amenity_id` | `amenities.id` | CASCADE |\n351: | `favorites` | `user_id` | `users.id` | CASCADE |\n352: | `favorites` | `property_id` | `properties.id` | CASCADE |\n353: | `inquiries` | `property_id` | `properties.id` | SET NULL |\n354: | `inquiries` | `user_id` | `users.id` | SET NULL |\n355: \n356: ### Relationship Details\n357: \n358: | Relationship | Type | Owner | Inverse | Junction |\n359: |-------------|------|-------|---------|----------|\n360: | User → RefreshToken | One-to-Many | — | RefreshToken.user ↔ User.refreshTokens | — |\n361: | User → PasswordResetToken | One-to-Many | — | PasswordResetToken.user ↔ User.resetTokens | — |\n362: | User → Favorite | One-to-Many | — | Favorite.user ↔ User.favorites | — |\n363: | User → Inquiry | One-to-Many | — | Inquiry.user ↔ User.inquiries | — |\n364: | Property → PropertyPhoto | One-to-Many | — | PropertyPhoto.property ↔ Property.photos | — |\n365: | Property → Favorite | One-to-Many | — | Favorite.property ↔ Property.favorites | — |\n366: | Property → Inquiry | One-to-Many | — | Inquiry.property ↔ Property.inquiries | — |\n367: | Property ↔ Amenity | Many-to-Many | Property (JoinTable) | Property.amenities ↔ Amenity.properties | `property_amenities` |\n368: \n369: ---\n370: \n371: ## Conventions\n372: \n373: ### Timestamps\n374: - All `timestamp` columns use `default: now()` for `created_at`.\n375: - `updated_at` is auto-managed by TypeORM (`@UpdateDateColumn`).\n376: - `deleted_at` is managed by TypeORM soft-delete (`@DeleteDateColumn`).\n377: \n378: ### Soft Delete\n379: - Enabled on: `users`, `properties`, `amenities`.\n380: - NOT enabled on: `refresh_tokens` (managed via `revoked_at` + `expires_at`), `password_reset_tokens` (managed via `expires_at` + `used_at`), `favorites` (hard delete on unfavorite), `inquiries` (retained indefinitely for audit), `property_photos` (hard delete on removal), `property_amenities` (junction – hard delete on unlink).\n381: \n382: ### Naming\n383: - **Tables**: `snake_case` plural (e.g., `property_photos`, `password_reset_tokens`)\n384: - **Columns**: `snake_case` (e.g., `user_id`, `property_type`, `address_city`)\n385: - **Enums**: PascalCase suffix `Enum` in TypeScript (e.g., `RoleEnum`, `PropertyTypeEnum`)\n386: \n387: ### Data Types\n388: - Monetary values: `decimal(10,2)` (supports prices up to $99,999,999.99)\n389: - Geo-coordinates: `decimal(10,7)` (sub-meter precision)\n390: - Percentages/ratios: `decimal(5,2)` if needed in future\n391: \n392: ---\n393: \n394: *Generated: 2026-05-19 | Source: PROJECT_KNOWLEDGE.md + PROJECT_API.md + database-patterns.md*\n\n(End of file - total 394 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# PROJECT_DATABASE\n\n## Schema Overview\n\nAll entities extend `BaseEntity` which provides:\n- `id` — UUID primary key\n- `createdAt` — `timestamp` (auto-managed)\n- `updatedAt` — `timestamp` (auto-managed)\n- `deletedAt` — `timestamp | null` (soft delete support)\n\nColumn naming convention: `snake_case` in the database (`@CreateDateColumn({ name: 'created_at' })`).\n\n---\n\n## Entities\n\n### User\n\nRepresents all registered users (Renters and Admins). Extends `BaseEntity` with soft delete.\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".claude-project/nestfind/docs/PROJECT_DATABASE.md","time":{"start":1779168815504,"end":1779168815918}},"id":"prt_e3eb9a40b001NrqBn52giFeUsV","sessionID":"ses_1c1475922ffeBFpIG9FNwSsGKw","messageID":"msg_e3eb8f212001hNn5U5YF16cY2I"}}
